'''Suwa Shrine''' (すわじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in Bessho-chō, {{jalink|Izumo City|Q825166}}, {{jalink|Shimane Prefecture|Q132751}}.

=== Overview ===
[[File:Bessho Suwa Jinja Keidai.jpg|thumb|Shrine grounds of Suwa Shrine|250px]]
The date of establishment is unknown, but there exists a {{jalink|munafuda|Q8008834}} (ridgepole inscription) dating from {{jalink|Tenshō|Q1145058}} 12{{sfn|Ashida, ed.|1930|p=272}}. There is a theory identifying this shrine with the “Izumo no Yashiro” recorded in the {{jalink|Izumo no Kuni Fudoki|Q11395858}} and the “{{jalink|Izumo Shrine (Engishiki)||Izumo Shrine}}” listed in the {{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}}{{sfn|Ashida, ed.|1930|p=272}}, but there are multiple candidate shrines for Izumo no Yashiro / Izumo Shrine, and criticism of the Suwa Shrine theory is strong{{sfn|Ishizuka|1986|pp=156–189}}.

In {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}} 5 (1872), it was designated a village shrine{{sfn|Takahashi|1983|p=515}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
'''{{jalink|Takeminakata-no-Kami}}'''
:According to the 18th-century topographical work {{jalink|Unyōshi}}, there was a rock cliff more than 40 ken high on Mount Miya, and beside it a round standing rock about 30 ken high and roughly 5 jō in circumference, called “Hobashira-ishi” or “{{ruby|檣|kachi|rp1=[|rp2=]}}-ishi”{{sfn|Ashida, ed.|1930|p=272}}{{efn|The Hobashira-ishi no longer exists{{sfn|Shimane Prefectural Shrine Association}}.}}. There is a tradition that when the monk Chishun, who founded {{jalink|Gakuen-ji|Q11674322}} located near Suwa Shrine, came from {{jalink|Shinano Province|Q289250}}, three old men welcomed him by boat and then divided the ship’s fittings and flew off to three places{{sfn|Ashida, ed.|1930|p=272}}. One of them was Suwa Myōjin; the fitting he took was the mast, which is said to be the Hobashira-ishi{{sfn|Ashida, ed.|1930|p=272}}.

'''{{jalink|Yatsukamizuomitsuno-no-Mikoto}}'''
:The {{jalink|Unyōshi}} states “it is Takeminakata-no-Mikoto,” and does not list Yatsukamizuomitsuno-no-Mikoto{{sfn|Ashida, ed.|1930|p=271}}.

